communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Malaria is endemic in Mindanao. Falciparum malaria accounts for 70 per
cent of all malaria cases in the Philippines and vivax malaria for the
remaining 30 per cent. In 2003, the country reported 47 677 confirmed
cases, giving an incidence of 0.55/1000 population. The main disease foci
are in remote rural areas of 25 endemic provinces (out of a total of 65
provinces).

In August 2002, the Philippines' New National Drug Policy was signed,
designating chloroquine plus sulfadoxinepyrimethamine combination therapy
as the 1st-line drug, artemether-lumefantrine(CoartemTM) as the 2nd-line
treatment, and quinine plus antibiotic (tetracycline, clindamycin, or
doxycycline) as the treatment regimen for severe malaria (see Review of the
malaria drug efficacy situation. WHO Western Pacific Region
<http://www.wpro.who.int/internet/resources.ashx/MVP/Review+of+the+Malaria+Drug+Efficacy.pdf>).
